# gha-dedup-jobs-trigger-scope-vs-workflow-call ‚Äî History

## v1.1.0 (2026-06-12)

ProjectHephaestus issue #1182 second review iteration (NOGO -> corrected)

**Verification:** unverified (still a planning artifact; not CI-validated)

**What changed:**

- Added a SAFETY GATE to decision-rule option (2) "trigger-scope the whole `on:`
  block": it is only safe if EVERY job in the workflow tolerates losing the event
  being removed. If any single job uniquely needs that event, drop to job-level
  `if:` granularity instead.
- Added job-level `if: github.event_name != 'pull_request'` (applied to ONLY the
  duplicate jobs) as the recommended granularity when a unique job needs the event.
  GitHub Actions triggers are WORKFLOW-WIDE, not per-job ‚Äî you cannot remove
  `on: pull_request` for only some jobs, so the per-job `if:` is the correct tool.
- Added a ROOT-CAUSE meta-lesson: ENUMERATE EVERY JOB IN THE FILE (read it
  end-to-end) before choosing a workflow-wide trigger change. An audit/issue-supplied
  line range is a STARTING POINT, not the file's full extent.
- Added a new Failed Attempts row: trigger-scoping the whole `on:` block to kill
  pip-audit/sast double-runs would have silently dropped `license-scan` ‚Äî a third
  PR-only blocking job in the SAME file (`security.yml` had three jobs, not two;
  the first plan read only `:18-96` and missed `:97-137`).
- Added a VERIFICATION REGRESSION GUARD requirement: any acceptance check must
  assert the unique job still runs on the event removed from the others (e.g.
  awk-assert `license-scan` has no `if:` before `runs-on`, and the `pull_request`
  trigger is still present). A naive `grep pull_request -> zero matches` check would
  have MASKED exactly this regression ‚Äî never write an acceptance check that passes
  in the regression state.
- Added the note that a GitHub `if:`-skipped job reports neutral/skipped (never
  failing), so skipping a non-required job on PRs is safe and won't block branch
  protection ‚Äî still verify the skipped job is not itself a required context.

**Why:** The original v1.0.0 decision rule offered only three coarse options
(delete / trigger-scope the whole workflow / workflow_call extraction). A second
review iteration on ProjectHephaestus issue #1182 proved that "trigger-scope the
whole workflow" has a DANGEROUS GAP: `security.yml` actually had THREE jobs
(`pip-audit`, `sast`, AND `license-scan`). `license-scan` (running
`scripts/check_license_compatibility.py`, which returns exit 1 only when
`GITHUB_EVENT_NAME == "pull_request"`, advisory exit 0 otherwise) exists ONLY in
`security.yml` and is BLOCKING ONLY on `pull_request`. Removing the workflow-wide
`pull_request` trigger to kill the pip-audit/sast duplication would have SILENTLY
DROPPED the only enforcing license-compatibility gate. That plan got a NOGO. The
corrected plan: keep the `pull_request` trigger; add
`if: github.event_name != 'pull_request'` to pip-audit and sast ONLY; leave
license-scan and the `on:` block untouched.

